Here is a basic example using HTML for the form and PHP for the server-side script to save the text to a file.

**1. Create the HTML form (save as `index.html`)**

This file creates a text area and a submit button. When the user clicks "Save Text," the form data is sent to `save_text.php`.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Text Input Form</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Enter Text to Save</h1>
    <form action="save_text.php" method="post">
        <textarea name="user_text" rows="10" cols="50" placeholder="Type your text here..." required></textarea>
        <br><br>
        <input type="submit" value="Save Text">
    </form>
</body>
</html>
```

**2. Create the PHP script (save as `save_text.php` in the same directory)**

This script receives the text from the form and appends it to a file named `saved_data.txt`.

```php
<?php
// Check if the form was submitted using the POST method
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    // Check if the 'user_text' field is not empty
    if (!empty($_POST['user_text'])) {
        // Get the text from the textarea
        $text = $_POST['user_text'];

        // Specify the file where the text will be saved
        $file = 'saved_data.txt';

        // Add a timestamp and a newline for better readability
        $content_to_save = "--- " . date("Y-m-d H:i:s") . " ---\n" . $text . "\n\n";

        // Append the content to the file
        // The FILE_APPEND flag ensures that the new text is added to the end of the file
        // The LOCK_EX flag prevents anyone else from writing to the file at the same time
        if (file_put_contents($file, $content_to_save, FILE_APPEND | LOCK_EX) !== false) {
            echo "Text saved successfully!";
        } else {
            echo "Error: Unable to save the text.";
        }

        // Provide a link to go back to the form
        echo '<br><a href="index.html">Enter more text</a>';

    } else {
        echo "No text was submitted.";
        echo '<br><a href="index.html">Go back</a>';
    }
} else {
    // If someone tries to access this file directly, redirect them to the form
    header('Location: index.html');
    exit();
}
?>
```

**How to use it:**

1.  Save both files (`index.html` and `save_text.php`) in the same directory on a web server that supports PHP.
2.  Open `index.html` in your web browser.
3.  Type text into the box and click "Save Text".
4.  A new file named `saved_data.txt` will be created (or updated) in the same directory, containing the text you submitted.
